es, and gender relations. This new image of the cycle as a detailed poetic frieze of ancient society eventually leads to a precise hypothesis concerning its literary and religious context in the Hellenistic age, as well as its geographical origins in the multiethnic borderland east of the Jordan. In a Jewish echo of anthropological skepticism, the poem emphasizes the plurality and relativity of the human condition while praising the communicative powers of pleasure, fantasy, and multifarious Eros.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access. Unless otherwise specified individually in the content, the work is licensed under the Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial-NoDerivatives (CC BY-NC-ND) license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/3.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aJudaismxHistoryyPost-exilic period, 586 B.C.-210 A.D. 0aSpace and timexBiblical teaching. 4aAmman. 4aDionysos. 4aHohelied. 4ahellenistisches Judentum. 7aRELIGION / Biblical Reference / Language Study.2bisacsh  aAmman.  aDionysus.  aHellenistic Judaism.  aSong of Songs.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2017 Part 1z978311076249508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2017z97831107195430 cEPUBz97831104988750 cprintz978311050054740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9783110500882zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110500882zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110500882/original  a978-3-11-071954-3 DG Plus eBook-Package 2017b2017  a978-3-11-076249-5 DG Plus DeG Package 2017 Part 1b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA